\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we have provided exact Bayesian methods for estimating the
 parameters of a multivariate Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process from discreetly
 observed time series.
 The parameters of the model generating the data are obtained from the MAP
 estimates which are derived using exact likelihood and sufficient statistics.
 The MAP estimates are obtained exactly, and thus the procedure does not
 require numerical minimization or Monte Carlo sampling, making it faster
 than the conventional Bayesian method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have provided two Bayesian methods for estimation of parameters.
 The first method uses exact expression for the likelihood, which is valid
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, and is obtained in terms four of sufficient statistics.
 This method is then reliable for low frequency of time series and provides
 large computational gains as we do not have to work with the entire time
 series but with four sufficient statistics.
 The second method uses the fact that, in equilibrium, only trap stiffness
 and mass can determine the fluctuations of position and velocity.
 Here, Gibbs distribution is then used to obtain the MAP estimates and the
 error bars.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have then applied the method to case of an underdamped Harmonics oscillator,
 which is a bivariate Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
 We find excellent agreements of the two methods and the simulation.
 We also compare our results with the traditional fitting methods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we have provided a method of model selection based on the estimation
 of evidence.
 The evidence is obtained in terms of the posterior probability and Ockham
 factor which penalizes for more parameters.
 Thus the interplay of posterior probability and the Ockham factor determine
 the best model for a given data.
\end_layout

